1 Names and values

This section is based on (Wickham 2019, Chapter 2)

1.1 Introduction

  • Goal: understand the distinction between names and values

  • Understand the distinction between an object and its name is helpful because you can:

    • Predict the performance and memory usage of your code

    • Write faster code by avoiding accidental copies

    • Understand Rs functional programming tools

Quiz

  1. Given the following data frame, how do I create a new column called 3 that contains the sum of 1 and 2? You may only use $, not [[. What makes 1, 2, and 3 challenging as variable names?
set.seed(1234)

df <- data.frame(runif(3), runif(3))
names(df) <- c(1, 2)
print(df)
##           1         2
## 1 0.1137034 0.6233794
## 2 0.6222994 0.8609154
## 3 0.6092747 0.6403106
df$"3" <- df$"1" + df$"2"
print(df)
##           1         2         3
## 1 0.1137034 0.6233794 0.7370829
## 2 0.6222994 0.8609154 1.4832148
## 3 0.6092747 0.6403106 1.2495853
  1. In the following code, how much memory does y occupy?
set.seed(1234)

x <- runif(1e6)
y <- list(x, x, x)

object.size(x)
## 8000048 bytes
object.size(y)
## 24000224 bytes

  • Why y is approximately the triple of x?

    • y contains copies of x
  1. On which line does a get copied in the following example?
a <- c(1, 5, 3, 2)
b <- a
b[[1]] <- 10
  • I assume that on the second line b <- a

1.2 Binding basics

Consider this code:

x <- 1:3

Its easy to read it as: create an object named x, containing the values 1, 2, and 3_. Unfortunately, thats a simplification that will lead to inaccurate.

A more accurate description is:

  • Creating an object, a vector of values, 1:3

  • Binding that object to a name, x

    • The object (or value) doesnt have a name. Its actually the name that has a value

To further clarify this distinction lets use a diagram where there is a binding from the name on the left-hand side to the object on the right-hand side:

include_graphics(path = "002_binding-1.png")

Source: (Wickham 2019, Chapter 2, Section 2.2)

For example, if you run this code, you dont get another copy of the value c(1, 2, 3), you get another binding to the existing object:

y <- x
include_graphics(path = "002_binding-2.png")

Source: (Wickham 2019, Chapter 2, Section 2.2)

You might have noticed that the value 1:3 has a label: 0x74b. While the vector doesnt have a name, we will occasionally need to refer to an object independent of its bindings. To make that possible, we will label values with a unique identifier. You can access an objects identifier with lobstr::obj_addr():

obj_addr(x)
## [1] "0xc087a08"
obj_addr(y)
## [1] "0xc087a08"

1.2.1 Non-syntactic names

R has strict rules about what constitutes a valid name:

  • Must consist of letters, digits, . and _

  • Cant begin with _ or a digit

  • You cant use any of the reserved words like TRUE, NULL, if, and function

    • see the complete list in ?Reserved

A name that doesnt follow these rules is a non-syntactic name. For example:


_abc <- 1
## Error: <text>:2:1: unexpected input
## 1: 
## 2: _
##    ^
if   <- 10
## Error: <text>:1:6: unexpected assignment
## 1: if   <-
##          ^

Its possible to override these rules and use any name. For example:

`_abc` <- 1
`if`   <- 10

Observation : You can also create non-syntactic bindings using single or double quotes (e.g."_abc" <- 1) instead of backticks, but you shouldnt, because youll have to use a different syntax to retrieve the values

1.2.2 Exercises

  1. Explain the relationship between a, b, c and d in the following code
a <- 1:10
b <- a
c <- b
d <- 1:10

  • a <- 1:10 means that <- assign the name a to the object 1:10 that has an associated identifier where we can access using lobstr::obj_addr(a)

    • obj_addr(a) gives the address of the value that a points to

  • b <- a means that <- assign the name b to the same object 1:10 where obj_addr(a) \(=\) obj_addr(b)

  • c <- b means that <- assign the name c to the same object 1:10 where obj_addr(b) \(=\) obj_addr(c)

map_lgl(.x = list(obj_addr(b), 
                  obj_addr(b), 
                  obj_addr(c)), 
        .f = identical, obj_addr(a))
## [1] TRUE TRUE TRUE
  • d <- 1:10 means that <- assign the name d to the object 1:10 but where obj_addr(d) \(\neq\) obj_addr(c)
map_lgl(.x = list(obj_addr(a), 
                  obj_addr(b), 
                  obj_addr(b), 
                  obj_addr(c)), 
        .f = identical, obj_addr(d))
## [1] FALSE FALSE FALSE FALSE
  1. The following code accesses the mean function in multiple ways. Do they all point to the same underlying function object? Verify this with lobstr::obj_addr()
  • mean
  • base::mean
  • get("mean")
  • evalq(mean)
  • match.fun("mean")

Creating all the possible functions \(f: A \rightarrow A\) where:

\[A = \{ \text{obj_addr(mean), obj_addr(base::mean), obj_addr(get("mean")), obj_addr(evalq(mean)), obj_addr(match.fun("mean"))} \}\]

without including the possibility of \(f(a) = a\) where \(a \in A\) and verifying if \(f(a) \equiv b\)

map_lgl(.x = list(obj_addr(base::mean), 
                  obj_addr(get("mean")), 
                  obj_addr(evalq(mean)), 
                  obj_addr(match.fun("mean"))), 
        .f = identical, obj_addr(mean))
## [1] TRUE TRUE TRUE TRUE
map_lgl(.x = list(obj_addr(get("mean")), 
                  obj_addr(evalq(mean)), 
                  obj_addr(match.fun("mean"))), 
        .f = identical, obj_addr(base::mean))
## [1] TRUE TRUE TRUE
map_lgl(.x = list(obj_addr(evalq(mean)), 
                  obj_addr(match.fun("mean"))), 
        .f = identical, obj_addr(get("mean")))
## [1] TRUE TRUE
map_lgl(.x = list(obj_addr(match.fun("mean"))), 
        .f = identical, obj_addr(evalq(mean)))
## [1] TRUE

  1. What rules does make.names() use to convert non-syntactic names into syntactic ones?

  • According to ?make.names:

    • The character X is prepended if necessary

    • All invalid characters are translated to .

    • A missing value is translated to NA

    • Names which match R keywords have a dot appended to them

    • Duplicated values are altered by make.unique

make.names(".123")
## [1] "X.123"
make.names("1$2 3")
## [1] "X1.2.3"
make.names(NA)
## [1] "NA."
make.names("for")
## [1] "for."
make.names(c("for", "for")) %>% make.unique()
## [1] "for."   "for..1"

  1. I slightly simplified the rules that govern syntactic names. Why is .123e1 not a syntactic name? Read ?make.names for the full details

    • According to ?makenames A syntactically valid name consists of letters, numbers and the dot or underline characters and starts with a letter or the dot not followed by a number. Names such as.2way" are not valid, and neither are the reserved words."

      • Therefore .123e1 is a non-syntactic name because the dot is follow by number \(1\)

1.3 Copy-on-modify

Consider the following code

x <- c(1, 2, 3)
y <- x



y[3] <- 4

print(x)
## [1] 1 2 3
print(y)
## [1] 1 2 4

Modifying y clearly didnt modify x

Observation In the case of Pythonthings are different:


x = [1, 2, 3]
y = x

y[2] = 4

print(x)
## [1, 2, 4]
print(y)
## [1, 2, 4]

If you expect the same result in Python as in R you can do this:


x = [1, 2, 3]
y = list(x)

y[2] = 4

print(x)
## [1, 2, 3]
print(y)
## [1, 2, 4]

While the value associated with y changed, the original object did not. Instead, R created a new object, 0xcd2, a copy of 0x74b with one value changed, then rebound y to that object:

include_graphics(path = "002_binding-3.png")

Source: (Wickham 2019, Chapter 2, Section 2.3)

This behavior is called copy-on-modify. However there are important exceptions to copy-on-modify that youll learn in the following sections

1.3.1 tracemem()

You can see when an object gets copied with the help of base::tracemem()

x <- c(1, 2, 3)

tracemem(x)
## [1] "<0000000018BB6AB0>"
y <- x

y[3] <- 4
## tracemem[0x0000000018bb6ab0 -> 0x0000000018e4c068]: eval eval withVisible withCallingHandlers handle timing_fn evaluate_call <Anonymous> evaluate in_dir block_exec call_block process_group.block process_group withCallingHandlers process_file <Anonymous> <Anonymous>
# untracemem() is the opposite of tracemem(); it turns tracing off
untracemem(x)

1.3.2 Function calls

The same rules for copying also apply to function calls. Take this code:

f <- function(a) {
  
  a
  
}

x <- 1:3

tracemem(x)
## [1] "<0000000014DD29B0>"
z <- f(x)

untracemem(x)

While f() is running, the a inside the function points to the same value as the x does outside the function:

include_graphics(path = "002_binding-f1.png")

Source: (Wickham 2019, Chapter 2, Section 2.3.2)

We will learn more about the conventions used in this diagram in Chapter 7

Once f() completes, x and z will point to the same object

obj_addr(x) == obj_addr(z)
## [1] TRUE
include_graphics(path = "002_binding-f2.png")

Source: (Wickham 2019, Chapter 2, Section 2.3.2)

1.3.3 Lists

Its not just names (i.e.variables) that point to values: elements of lists do too

l1 <- list(1, 2, 3)

However lists are more complex because instead of storing values, they store references to them:

include_graphics(path = "002_list.png")

Source: (Wickham 2019, Chapter 2, Section 2.3.3)

For example if you modify a list

l2 <- l1

l2[[3]] <- 4

Initially you have

include_graphics(path = "002_l-modify-1.png")

Source: (Wickham 2019, Chapter 2, Section 2.3.3)

But then after the modification you have

include_graphics(path = "002_l-modify-2.png")

Source: (Wickham 2019, Chapter 2, Section 2.3.3)

Like vectors, lists use copy-on-modify behavior; the original list is left unchanged, and R creates a modified copy. This, however, is a shallow copy: the list object and its bindings are copied, but the values pointed to by the bindings are not.

To see values that are shared across lists, use lobstr::ref()

print(ref(l1, l2))
## o [1:0x1aaf68e0] <list> 
## +-[2:0x16ffe818] <dbl> 
## +-[3:0x16ffe7e0] <dbl> 
## \-[4:0x16ffe7a8] <dbl> 
##  
## o [5:0x1b01ccb0] <list> 
## +-[2:0x16ffe818] 
## +-[3:0x16ffe7e0] 
## \-[6:0x17096d80] <dbl>

1.4 Data frames

Data frames are lists of vectors, so copy-on-modify has important consequences when you modify a data frame

d1 <- data.frame(x = c(1, 5, 6), 
                 y = c(2, 4, 3))
include_graphics(path = "002_dataframe.png")

Source: (Wickham 2019, Chapter 2, Section 2.3.4)

If you modify a column, only that column needs to be modified

d2 <- d1

d2[, 2] <- d2[, 2] + 1 

print(ref(d1, d2))
## o [1:0x1a009750] <df[,2]> 
## +-x = [2:0x20b4e880] <dbl> 
## \-y = [3:0x20b4e830] <dbl> 
##  
## o [4:0x1a9e3930] <df[,2]> 
## +-x = [2:0x20b4e880] 
## \-y = [5:0x229a2150] <dbl>
include_graphics(path = "002_d-modify-c.png")

Source: (Wickham 2019, Chapter 2, Section 2.3.4)

However, if you modify a row, every column is modified:

d3 <- d1

d3[2, ] <- d3[2, ] + 1

print(ref(d1, d3))
## o [1:0x1a009750] <df[,2]> 
## +-x = [2:0x20b4e880] <dbl> 
## \-y = [3:0x20b4e830] <dbl> 
##  
## o [4:0x1b009248] <df[,2]> 
## +-x = [5:0x231d1490] <dbl> 
## \-y = [6:0x231d13f0] <dbl>
include_graphics(path = "002_d-modify-r.png")

Source: (Wickham 2019, Chapter 2, Section 2.3.4)

1.4.1 Character vectors

The final place that R uses references is with character vectors

x <- c("a", "a", "abc", "d")
include_graphics(path = "002_character.png")

Source: (Wickham 2019, Chapter 2, Section 2.3.5)

But this is a polite fiction. R actually uses a global string pool where each element of a character vector is a pointer to a unique string in the pool

include_graphics(path = "002_character-2.png")

You can request that ref() show these references:

print(ref(x, character = TRUE))
## o [1:0x2371a538] <chr> 
## +-[2:0x6bee828] <string: "a"> 
## +-[2:0x6bee828] 
## +-[3:0x1a106e38] <string: "abc"> 
## \-[4:0x6dbb550] <string: "d">
